#Text=CHAPTER I
#Text=It was four o’clock in the morning when George Dupont closed the door and came down the steps to the street .

#Text=The first faint streaks of dawn were in the sky , and he noticed this with annoyance , because he knew that his hair was in disarray and his whole aspect disorderly ; yet he dared not take a cab , because he feared to attract attention at home .
#Text=When he reached the sidewalk , he glanced about him to make sure that no one had seen him leave the house , then started down the street , his eyes upon the sidewalk before him .
#Text=George had the feeling of the morning after .
#Text=There are few men in this world of abundant sin who will not know what the phrase means .
#Text=The fumes of the night had evaporated ; he was quite sober now , quite free from excitement .
#Text=He saw what he had done , and it seemed to him something black and disgusting .
#Text=Never had a walk seemed longer than the few blocks which he had to traverse to reach his home .
#Text=He must get there before the maid was up , before the baker ’s boy called with the rolls ; otherwise , what explanation could he give ?
#Text=-- he who had always been such a moral man , who had been pointed out by mothers as an example to their sons .
#Text=George thought of his own mother , and what she would think if she could know about his night ’s adventure .
#Text=He thought again and again , with a pang of anguish , of Henriette .

#Text=Could it be possible that a man who was engaged , whose marriage contract had actually been signed , who was soon to possess the love of a beautiful and noble girl -- that such a man could have been weak enough and base enough to let himself be trapped into such a low action ?
#Text=He went back over the whole series of events , shuddering at them , trying to realize how they had happened , trying to excuse himself for them .
#Text=He had not intended such a culmination ; he had never meant to do such a thing in his life .
#Text=He had not thought of any harm when he had accepted the invitation to the supper party with his old companions from the law school .
#Text=Of course , he had known that several of these chums led “ fast ” lives -- but , then , surely a fellow could go to a friend ’s rooms for a lark without harm !
#Text=He remembered the girl who had sat by his side at the table .
#Text=She had come with a friend who was a married woman , and so he had assumed that she was all right .
#Text=George remembered how embarrassed he had been when first he had noticed her glances at him .
#Text=But then the wine had begun to go to his head -- he was one of those unfortunate wretches who cannot drink wine at all .
#Text=He had offered to take the girl home in a cab , and on the way he had lost his head .
#Text=Oh !
#Text=What a wretched thing it was .
#Text=He could hardly believe that it was he who had spoken those frenzied words ; and yet he must have spoken them , because he remembered them .
#Text=He remembered that it had taken a long time to persuade her .
#Text=He had had to promise her a ring like the one her married friend wore .
#Text=Before they entered her home she had made him take off his shoes , so that the porter might not hear them .

#Text=This had struck George particularly , because , even flushed with excitement as he was , he had not forgotten the warnings his father had given him as to the dangers of contact with strange women .
#Text=He had thought to himself , “ This girl must be safe .
#Text=It is probably the first time she has ever done such a thing . ”
#Text=But now George could get but little consolation out of that idea .
#Text=He was suffering intensely -- the emotion described by the poet in the bitter words about “ Time ’s moving finger having writ . ”
#Text=His mind , seeking some explanation , some justification , went back to the events before that night .
#Text=With a sudden pang of yearning , he thought of Lizette .
#Text=She was a decent girl , and had kept him decent , and he was lonely without her .

#Text=He had been so afraid of being found out that he had given her up when he became engaged ; but now for a while he felt that he would have to break his resolution , and pay his regular Sunday visit to the little flat in the working-class portion of Paris .
#Text=It was while George was fitting himself for the same career as his father -- that of notary -- that he had made the acquaintance of the young working girl .
#Text=It may not be easy to believe , but Lizette had really been a decent girl .
#Text=She had a family to take care of , and was in need .

#Text=There was a grandmother in poor health , a father not much better , and three little brothers ; so Lizette did not very long resist George Dupont , and he felt quite virtuous in giving her sufficient money to take care of these unfortunate people .
#Text=Among people of his class it was considered proper to take such things if one paid for them .
#Text=All the family of this working girl were grateful to him .
#Text=They adored him , and they called him Uncle Raoul ( for of course he had not been so foolish as to give them his true name ) .
